on-arrival: columna_last = time

= La deriva

Hunger does to guerrillas what it does to everyone, only with guns in the room. A column cut off too long — low on materiel, lower on wins, out of contact with the leadership for a season — has started doing the thing every armed movement dreads and most eventually do: living off the very people it exists to defend. Not expropriation with receipts, the way Lucio taught; just taking. A store here, a truck there, and the villages beginning to lock their doors against the men who were supposed to be the answer.

The war does not end when the army wins. It ends when the people stop being able to tell you apart from the bandits — and that ending has begun, in one column, this month.

- @deriva_rescatar: Reach them: resupply, re-contact, remind them what they are. Spend what it takes to pull a column back from the edge.
- @deriva_disolver: Dissolve it. Some columns cannot be saved, only ended before they discredit the whole war — bring them down or cut them loose.
- @deriva_ignorar: Nothing to spare. Let the column fend for itself and hope the drift reverses on its own.

@deriva_rescatar
go-to: post_event
choose-if: funds >= 5 and organizers >= 2
unavailable-subtitle: Pulling a column back from banditry takes cash and trusted cadres — 5 funds, 2 organizers.
on-arrival: funds -= 5; moral_columnas += 14; sup_peasants += 2; guerrilla_meter += 1; unity += 2

An emissary the column respects goes up with money, medicine, and the harder cargo: the reminder, delivered at a fire, of why anyone climbed the mountain in the first place. It works, mostly, because the drift shamed them too — men become bandits by degrees and hate themselves the whole way. The column re-enters discipline thinner and quieter, and the villages, watching the doors it stops needing to be locked, extend one more season of the only thing that keeps a guerrilla alive: the benefit of the doubt.

@deriva_disolver
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: moral_columnas += 4; pres_guerrero -= 5; members += 1; unity -= 2; guerrilla_meter -= 2

The order is the hardest a leadership gives: it is over, come down or scatter, the column is dissolved before its hunger writes a chapter the enemy's press will quote for decades. Some come down; some vanish into the day labor of the defeated; a few refuse and become, exactly as feared, a small horror with a red flag that the state will point to forever. You saved the war's name by ending a piece of the war. In this decade that is sometimes the whole of command.

@deriva_ignorar
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: moral_columnas -= 6; sup_peasants -= 5; represion += 2; memorial += 1; guerrilla_meter -= 1

You have nothing to send and you send nothing, and the drift does what drift does: the column crosses the line from movement to menace, a village files a complaint the army is delighted to answer, and a firefight that should have been against soldiers happens instead over a stolen truck. The war loses a column and a region's trust in the same month, to no enemy but its own hunger. The manuals have a cold name for it — *lumpenización* — and no cure but the resupply you could not afford.
